h3. Issue Summary

As a Confluence Cloud administrator, one of the things you can do is to import spaces from other Confluence sites.
 Apparently, in case you are not a site-admin within the site, you are not able to import the space due to a weird error: "_EmailNotInDrsList_"
h3. Steps to Reproduce
 # Export a space to XML from a site you have access to;
 # Logging in with a user that is not a site-admin but a Confluence administrator, log in to a different Confluence Cloud site;
 # Navigate to *Settings > Import space*, and import the space you exported on step *#1*.

h3. Expected Results

The space gets imported successfully.
h3. Actual Results
 * An error prevents you to import the space:
{code:java}
{"errorType":"EmailNotInDrsList","message":"Email domain is not in the DRS list","data":"<domain>"}
{code}
* There is also an additional error that can be displayed when non site-admins attempt the space import:

{code}
{"errorType":"PublicSignUpDisabled","message":"Public Sign up is not enabled"}
{code}

 * In addition to that, according to the [space import|https://support.atlassian.com/confluence-cloud/docs/import-a-confluence-cloud-space/] documentation, this procedure "_will not import user accounts_", but it actually adds the users to the site userbase but with no product access, though as active users - that might be the reason why non-site-admins cannot perform this action.

h3. Workaround

Engage one of your site-admins to make you a site-admin, so then you will be able to import spaces.

h3. Summary
Currently, if we type 1 + . (dot), then space, Confluence will read it as a numbered list and will format it accordingly.

h3. Suggestion
* Add an option at the Confluence user profile level that allows individual users to disable the auto-formatting for numbered lists.

h3. Workaround
# Hit _1_ ;
# Then space;
# Then dot;
# Then space again;
# Place the mouse cursor after the first space and delete it;
# Place the mouse cursor back to after the second space.

h3. Summary

By default, when editing tables in Confluence, users will have different keyboard shortcuts such as the ones to insert columns and rows.

While this helps on the productivity to add content, modifying or deleting content on the table still requires manual interaction via the UI.
h3. Suggestion

This is a suggestion to add additional keyboard shortcuts to make it quicker to edit table content. For example:
 * Remove rows and columns;
 * Merge and split cells;
 * Table options (header, row, numbered column);
 * Open the cell background color pop-up;

Please, add official support to Vivaldi browser, as it is getting traction among developers, and it's Chromium-based anyway.

